<DIV1 TYPE="appendix">
<PB N="27" REF="002780_0033_0FE632A06E072848">
<HEAD><HI>APPENDIX.</HI> THERE has fallen into our hands a private Letter of the late Reverend Dr. <HI>Increa&s;e Mather</HI>'s, upon the Sub|ject of the foregoing Pages, written to one of his Neighbours: A Copy of which we think fit to annex; and <HI>by it, He being dead, yet &s;peaketh.</HI> 'Tis as follows:</HEAD>
<OPENER><SALUTE><HI>Brother</HI> &mdash;</SALUTE></OPENER>
<P>ALTHO' I am fuller of Bu&s;ine&s;s than I have been (to my knowledge) ever &s;ince my coming to <HI>Bo&s;ton,</HI> yet out of re&s;pect to my <HI>Word,</HI> and my Love to <HI>You,</HI> I &s;end you the following &s;hort An&s;wer, to the <HI>Que&s;tion,</HI> upon which you de&s;ired my Apprehen&s;ions.</P>
<P><HI>QUESTION,</HI></P>
<P><HI>WHETHER it be Lawful for a Church-Member among us, to be frequently in Taverns</HI>?</P>
<P><HI>ANSWER,</HI></P>
<P>In the following <HI>PROPOSITIONS,</HI></P>
<P N="1"><PB N="28" REF="002780_0034_0FE632A0717623D0"><HI>I.</HI> It is <HI>not</HI> Lawful for a Church-Member to be in <HI>Taverns</HI> oftner than <HI>Nece&s;&s;ity</HI> calleth for it.</P>
<P>And this is evident,</P>
<P N="1">1. Becau&s;e we are to <HI>Ab&s;tain from all Appearance of Evil,</HI> 1 <HI>The&s;.</HI> V. 22. <HI>Jude</HI> 23. Now, This has an <HI>Appearance of Evil.</HI> It looks &s;omething like being a <HI>Pot-Companion.</HI></P>
<P N="2">2. Becau&s;e we mu&s;t avoid all <HI>Temptations to Sin.</HI> Where any Evil is <HI>forbidden,</HI> it is <HI>required</HI> that the <HI>Temptations</HI> leading to that Evil, &s;hould be &s;hunned. Therefore the Rule that forbids <HI>Drunkenne&s;s,</HI> does al&s;o prohibit being unnece&s;&s;arily where there is <HI>much Drink</HI> a going, that may be a <HI>Temptation to Exce&s;s. Gen.</HI> XXXIX. 10. <HI>Prov.</HI> V. 8.</P>
<P N="3">3. Becau&s;e we mu&s;t, as much as may be, avoid the giving of <HI>Occa&s;ion unto others</HI> to Sin. Yea, a Chri&s;tian &s;hould abridge him&s;elf of his <HI>lawful Liberty,</HI> if it prove an <HI>Occa&s;ion</HI> for others to Sin again&s;t GOD. And therefore the Apo&s;tle forbids Eating in an <HI>Idols Temple</HI>: Not but that it was in it &s;elf Law|ful to Eat <HI>there,</HI> or in any other Place; becau&s;e no Places under the <HI>Go&s;pel</HI> are either Holy or Profane, as under the <HI>Law</HI>: but becau&s;e &s;ome would by that means be occa&s;ioned to commit <HI>Idolatry,</HI> and be hardned in Sin, 1 <HI>Cor.</HI> VIII. 9, 10, 11, 12, 13.</P>
<P N="2"><HI>II.</HI> For Church-Members to <HI>Chu&s;e</HI> to tran&s;act their <HI>Civil, Affairs</HI> in the <HI>Tavern</HI>&punc; when they might as well do it at their own Hou&s;es, is an Evil in the Sight of GOD.</P>
<P>For,</P>
<P N="1">1. They <HI>occa&s;ion others to Sin</HI> again&s;t GOD. The more Carnal &s;ort of People will &s;ay, <HI>Such and &s;uch are often in Taverns, for all they make a Pro|fe&s;&s;ion of Religion, and are Members of Churche.</HI> Thus the <HI>way of Truth is evil &s;poken of.</HI> And tho'
<PB N="29" REF="002780_0035_0FE632A72DF82870">
<HI>Godly</HI> Per&s;ons may go into the <HI>Tavern</HI> for lawful Ends, to di&s;patch their lawful Affairs, yet the <HI>Un|godly</HI> will from thence take Advantage to follow <HI>Taverns</HI> for unlawful Ends, even to <HI>Drink</HI> and be <HI>Drunken</HI> there. Now, a Chri&s;tian &s;hould be very Tender of <GAP DESC="illegible" REASON="torn page" EXTENT="1 span"> &s;o much as an Occa&s;ion of Di&s;ho|nour to <GAP DESC="illegible" REASON="torn page" EXTENT="1 span"> of wrong to the Souls of any. 2 <HI>Sam.</HI> <GAP DESC="illegible" REASON="torn page" EXTENT="1 span"> XXII. 22. <HI>Rom.</HI> XIV. 13. <HI>Gal.</HI> <GAP DESC="illegible" REASON="torn page" EXTENT="1 span"> 14. 1 <HI>Joh.</HI> II. 10.</P>
<P>Yea, <GAP DESC="illegible" REASON="torn page" EXTENT="1 span"> <GAP DESC="illegible" REASON="torn page" EXTENT="2 letters">uld endeavour to walk &s;o as to cut off all <GAP DESC="illegible" REASON="torn page" EXTENT="1 span">, of Evil-&s;peaking, or Evil-think|ing, or Evil-doing, from them that are &s;o Wicked as to &s;eek Occa&s;ion. 2 <HI>Cor.</HI> XI. 12.</P>
<P N="2">2. When Men do thus <HI>unnece&s;&s;arily frequent Ta|verns,</HI> it <GAP DESC="illegible" REASON="torn page" EXTENT="1 word"> be Ju&s;t with GOD, to <HI>leave them</HI> to fall into <GAP DESC="illegible" REASON="torn page" EXTENT="1 word"> If a Man <HI>wilfully</HI> for&s;ake GOD in never &s;o &s;mall <GAP DESC="illegible" REASON="torn page" EXTENT="1 word"> <GAP DESC="illegible" REASON="torn page" EXTENT="2 letters">tter, he may well fear that GOD will for&s;ake him. 2 <HI>Chron.</HI> XV. 2. <HI>P&s;al.</HI> LXXXI. 11, 12.</P>
<P N="3">3. <HI>III</HI> IT is not unlawful for a Church-Member to go into the Tavern, when the Bu&s;ine&s;s of his Civil Calling does <HI>nece&s;&s;arily</HI> Call him thereunto.</P>
<P>And this is evident,</P>
<P N="1">1. Becau&s;e a <HI>Tavern</HI> is not in it &s;elf an <HI>unlawful Place.</HI> We read of <HI>Inns</HI> in the Scripture; and of Good Men that when called thereunto, have gone into them. <HI>Gen.</HI> XLII. 27. <HI>Exod.</HI> IV. 24. <HI>Luk.</HI> II. 7.</P>
<P N="2">2. Becau&s;e the Duties of a Man's <HI>General,</HI> and of his <HI>Particular</HI> Calling, may &s;tand well together. A Man's <HI>General Calling,</HI> as he is a Chri&s;tian, does not Nullify, but rather Confirm his <HI>Particular Calling,</HI> and makes it &s;anctified unto him. *** 1 <HI>Cor.</HI> VII. 20. &mdash; V. 10.</P>
<P N="4"><HI>IV.</HI> If a Church-Member be Nece&s;&s;itated to be in the <HI>Tavern,</HI> he ought to carry him&s;elf <HI>Circum|&s;pectly there.</HI></P>
<P><PB N="30" REF="002780_0036_0FE632AD48217390">The Rea&s;on is,</P>
<P N="1">1. Becau&s;e he is in <HI>more danger</HI> of &s;inning there, than at other times; by means of divers Tempta|tions that are before him.</P>
<P N="2">2. Becau&s;e by a Circum&s;pect a<GAP DESC="illegible" REASON="torn page" EXTENT="2 letters"> <GAP DESC="illegible" REASON="torn page" EXTENT="1 span"> <GAP DESC="illegible" REASON="torn page" EXTENT="1 letter">arriage, others may be drawn to glorify <GAP DESC="illegible" REASON="torn page" EXTENT="1 span"> <HI><GAP DESC="illegible" REASON="torn page" EXTENT="3 letters">ewi&s;e. Matth.</HI> V. 16. 1 <HI>Pet.</HI> II. 12.&mdash; I<GAP DESC="illegible" REASON="torn page" EXTENT="1 letter"> <GAP DESC="illegible" REASON="torn page" EXTENT="1 span"></P>
<P>Thus I have given you a <GAP DESC="illegible" REASON="torn page" EXTENT="1 span"> to your Enquiry. The Lord be wit<GAP DESC="illegible" REASON="torn page" EXTENT="1 letter"> <GAP DESC="illegible" REASON="torn page" EXTENT="1 span"> <GAP DESC="illegible" REASON="torn page" EXTENT="1 letter">nd guide you into all ways of well-plea&s;ing before Him! I am,</P>
<CLOSER><SIGNED>Your loving Fri<GAP DESC="illegible" REASON="torn page" EXTENT="3 letters"> <HI>Increa&s;e Mather.</HI></SIGNED></CLOSER>
</DIV1>
